  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This Dryad dataset, deposited in 2023 by a large team at Johns Hopkins University led by Ted and Valina Dawson, underpins research into how dysregulated mTORC1 signaling and aberrant protein synthesis contribute to alpha-synuclein-driven neurodegeneration in Parkinson's disease. The dataset has attracted 153 views and 16 downloads on Dryad, and its findings have been taken up in at least two published works, including a study in <em>Science Translational Medicine</em>.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The dataset supports a study examining a mechanistically important question in Parkinson's disease research: whether pathologic forms of alpha-synuclein perturb the mTORC1 signaling axis to drive excessive protein synthesis and disrupt proteostasis. The work, conducted entirely within Johns Hopkins University, employs both cellular and animal models to interrogate the PI3K/AKT/mTOR pathway, autophagy, and downstream translational regulation. The breadth of the contributing team \u2014 at least nineteen authors \u2014 reflects the multidisciplinary scope required to bridge molecular cell biology with in vivo neuroscience.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">In terms of scholarly uptake, the dataset's most significant signal is its citation by a paper published in <em>Science Translational Medicine</em>, a high-impact translational journal, as well as by a preprint registered in late 2022. These linkages indicate that the underlying data are actively informing ongoing research in the neurodegeneration field, even if formal citation counts for the dataset record itself remain nascent \u2014 a common pattern for data deposits whose impact is channelled primarily through the associated journal article rather than the Dryad entry directly.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Usage metrics on Dryad show 153 views against 16 downloads, a view-to-download ratio that suggests a broad audience scanning the resource but a more selective group proceeding to acquire the raw data. This pattern is typical for specialized experimental datasets in molecular neuroscience, where the primary consumers are researchers with the technical infrastructure to analyze complex signaling or proteomic data. The dataset is openly accessible under Dryad's standard open-access terms, consistent with the green open-access status of the broader work.</p>\n\n<p class=\"story-text\">Conceptually, the dataset sits at the intersection of some of the most active areas in neurodegeneration research. mTORC1-mediated control of protein homeostasis is increasingly recognized as a convergence point linking genetic and environmental risk factors in Parkinson's disease, and autophagy impairment downstream of mTOR hyperactivation is a candidate mechanism for the accumulation of toxic alpha-synuclein species. By making the underlying experimental data publicly available, the Dawson laboratory enables independent replication and secondary analyses, supporting the broader scientific community's efforts to validate and extend these mechanistic insights toward therapeutic targets.</p>",
